com.ibm.jaggr.core.deps

Class ModuleDepInfo

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.ibm.jaggr.core.deps.ModuleDepInfo
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable

    public class ModuleDepInfo
extends Object
implements Serializable
    Encapsulates dependency meta-data for an AMD module. This includes has! plugin conditionals used in has! plugin branching during require list expansion and optional trace comments.
    See Also:

      • getHasPluginPrefixes

        public Collection<String> getHasPluginPrefixes(Map<?,?> formulaCache)
        A return value of null means that the associated module should be included in the expanded dependency list unconditionally. A return value consisting of an empty list means that it should not be included at all.

        If the list is not empty, then the list elements are the has! plugin prefixes that should be used with this module. One module id per list entry specifying the same module name should be used.

        TreeSet is used to obtain predictable ordering of terms in compound has conditionals, mostly for unit tests.

        Parameters:
        formulaCache - the formula cache
        Returns:
        The list of has! plugin prefixes for this module.

      • containsTerm

        public boolean containsTerm(BooleanTerm term)
        Returns true if the specified term is logically included by the formula for this object.

        Put another way, this method returns true if adding the specified term to the formula for this object does not change the truth table for the formula.

        Parameters:
        term - The term to test for logical inclusion
        Returns:
        True if the formula logically includes the specified term

      • subtract

        public boolean subtract(ModuleDepInfo toSub)
        Logically subtracts the boolean terms in the specified object from the boolean formula in this object. This means that if a term from the specified object logically includes a term from this object, then the term from this object will be removed.

        A term logically includes another term if it evaluates to the same result for all vars within the term. For example, the term A contains (A*B), but not vice-versa.

        Parameters:
        toSub - The object to subtract from this object
        Returns:
        True if this object was modified
